<h2>What is a wallet?</h2>
<p>Think of a wallet as like a master account where you can manage all of your digital assets and NFTs. A user can manage multiple addresses (accounts) with their wallet.</p>
<br>

<h3>WTF?</h3>
<p>Wallets function just like accounts on popular websites. Users can log into their wallet and view all of their crypto accounts, like a dash board. Because the account exists on the blockchain, a decentralized public network, the user is the sole owner of the account: that means the user is the sole owner of all assets and the sole controller of all transactions of the account, unlike conventional applications such as banks or social media companies.</p>
<br>

<h2>What is an address?</h2>

<p>A wallet can generate addresses for users to deposit funds. Each address functions as its own individual account and every address is identified by a long and unique string of random characters.</p>
<br>

<h3>WTF?</h3>
<p>An address functions as a unique way of identifying your account as it is a very long string of numbers that are randomly generated. The odds of generating an identical account are XXX. Keep in mind that an address and wallet are not the same thing, as your wallet can manage multiple addresses.</p>

<h2>Transacting:</h2>
<p>Sending funds to an address functions exactly like modern digital banking in many countries. To send or receive funds, simply copy and paste the unique address number of the recipient (like an IBAN number).</p>
<br>

<h3>WTF?</h3>
<p>Transactions to and from an address on the blockchain function very much like shipping a package to a physical address:</p>
